<body>
      <p> Nagpur, known as the "Orange City" and the winter capital of Maharashtra, is famous for its high-quality citrus fruit production. 
Situated at the "Geographical Center of India," it is a major trade hub for oranges, rich in history, and a gateway to numerous tiger reserves, earning it the title "Tiger Capital of India". </p>
<p1>
 Top Cultural & Historical Landmarks
Orange City: Known globally as the "Orange City" because it is a leading producer and distribution hub for high-quality, juicy oranges.
Deekshabhoomi: A major Buddhist pilgrimage site featuring the world's largest hollow stupa. It marks the spot where Dr. B.R. Ambedkar converted to Buddhism in 1956.
Zero Mile Marker: A sandstone pillar used by the British to mark the exact geographical center of undivided India.
Religious Sites: Home to prominent temples like the Ganesh Tekdi Mandir, the Dragon Palace Temple (symbolizing Indo-Japanese friendship), and the Ramtek Fort Temple, where Lord Rama is believed to have rested. </p1>
<p2>
 Food & Local Specialties
Saoji Cuisine: A signature spicy and fiery style of cooking unique to the Vidarbha region.
Tarri Poha: The iconic Nagpuri breakfast consisting of flattened rice topped with a spicy chickpea curry (tarri).
Orange Barfi: A popular sweet made from local oranges.
Haldiram's: The globally renowned snacks and sweets brand originated here. </p2>

